        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Charleston S. C. March 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1879.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd. S. Morais<lb/>
                Philad.<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Will you please inform me<lb/> as to the meaning and correct application<lb/> of the word &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#63;  Am I correct in the opinion<lb/> that the word was used distinctively as the<lb/> appellation of the Deity by the Hebrews&#59; just<lb/> as Baal Dagon Ashtaroth etc were em&#45;<lb/>ployed by other nations as the proper name<lb/> of their conception of the godhead&#63;  Can<lb/> I then translated thus&#58; &#34;Hear O Israel Adonai<lb/> is our God&#44; Adonai is One.&#34;  But if Adonai<lb/> was only a substitution for the ineffable name<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; and not particularly the name by<lb/> which the God of the <sic>hebrews</sic> was<lb/> known&#44; is not &#34;Eternal&#34; the better trans&#45;<lb/>lation <del>of</del> in the sentence and not &#34;Lord&#34;<lb/> Yet &#34;Eternal&#34; is not the <del>best</del> most correct&#44; if we<lb/> consider that the Deity of the nations<lb/> was conceived by them to be Eternal&#44;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>and I am led to believe that Adonai ought<lb/> not be translated.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am sorry I was unable to see you when<lb/> I called.  I intended to remain a week<lb/> longer&#44; but received a telegram that<lb/> same day informing me of sickness in<lb/> the family here.  Thank God all<lb/> are well again.  Wishing the same<lb/> for you &#38; yours.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am<lb/>
                Dr. Sir.<lb/>
                Yours Very Truly<lb/>
                David Levy.<lb/></p>
            <p>106 Wentworth St.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
